wn age. Illuminating the poetic strategies Keats, Austen, Byron, and Hazlitt used to convey that sense of mystery, Rohrbach describes a poetic grammar of future anteriority—of uncertainty concerning what will have been. Romantic writers, she shows, do not simply reflect the history of their time; their works make imaginable a new way of thinking the historical present when faced with the temporalities of modernity.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aEnglish literaturey18th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aEnglish literaturey19th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aLiterature and historyzGreat BritainxHistoryy18th century. 0aLiterature and historyzGreat BritainxHistoryy19th century. 0aPoeticsxHistoryy18th century. 0aPoeticsxHistoryy19th century. 0aRomanticismzGreat Britain. 0aTime in literature. 4aLiterary Studies. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Poetry.2bisacsh  aAusten.  aByron.  aDon Juan.  aFuture.  aKeats.  aPersuasion.  aTemporality.  ahistoriography.  apoetics.  aromanticism.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertFordham University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311072903040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780823267996zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780823267996423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780823267996/original  a978-3-11-072903-0  Fordham University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK